@tlively, Binaryen is a big hammer doing substantial rewrites, so not necessarily representative. Do we know the same is true for, say, the likes of wasm-ld? Are there others? I alone hacked together several static wasm linkers in the past (a substrate is [this one](https://github.com/WebAssembly/gc/tree/waml/proposals/gc/wln)), and none did any of that. For such tools, it would be a breaking change.

Fundamentally, I still think this is entangling two unrelated features that should remain independent. I am not convinced changing it for imports is worth it, given that nobody ever missed it? From my perspective, it'd be doing more harm than good.

@eqrion, fair enough, although I wish we could try.

@eqrion, a merger statically links two (or N) modules by resolving export/import pairs between them and then "concatenating" the module bodies. Beyond that, it shouldn't have to do more than shifting indices accordingly. It could keep resolved exports, but it certainly can't keep resolved imports, which is why imports are the bigger issue.

That said, even for exports, multiple "resolved" exports from different modules (when merging more than two) could happen to have a name clash. Or you don't want to expose what becomes an implementation detail of the combined module. So in fact it would be preferable if exports didn't have implicit extra meaning either (and I'd like to shift away a bit from my earlier statement about exports).

Wrt modules, it always comes down to the same observation: attaching any implicit meaning to imports, exports, or module boundaries conflicts with inter-module composability/transformability, notwithstanding intra-module convenience.

